test-longmath: 64-bit (long long / unsigned long long) arithmetic on objtype=riscv64

WHAT IS TESTED
--------------
9 checks over UART0, all built from small (safely-in-32-bit-range) seed
values passed through vid()/uvid() - trivial identity functions, same
technique as val()/uval() in test-divmod - so nothing is a compile-time
constant and every interesting 64-bit value is constructed at runtime,
usually two different ways, rather than written as a large literal:

  - 1<<32 built via a single shift-by-32 vs via two shift-by-16 -
    checks these agree (in case exactly-32 is special-cased somewhere).
  - (1<<32)-1, then +1, checks the carry propagates back into the high
    32 bits correctly.
  - Two 64-bit relational compares (1<<32 > 0xFFFFFFFF, 1<<32 < 1)
    picked so that a hypothetical bug comparing only the low 32 bits
    would give the WRONG answer, not coincidentally agree with the
    correct 64-bit answer - a comparison that happens to agree either
    way wouldn't actually catch anything.
  - 100000*100000 (10,000,000,000, overflows 32 bits) checked against
    the same product built from a different factorization
    (100000*50000*2) - a real 64-bit MUL, not two 32-bit MULs that
    happen to look right.
  - 1<<40 via a single shift-by-40 vs two shift-by-20 - same reasoning
    as the 1<<32 check, and confirms the shift amount itself (40) isn't
    masked down (RV64's SLL uses the low 6 bits of the shift amount,
    not 5 - an easy off-by-one for code inherited from a 32-bit-only
    backend).
  - (1u<<63) (top bit only) compared as unsigned (> 0, true) and as
    signed (< 0, true) - checks unsigned vs signed 64-bit comparison is
    genuinely distinct, same idea as test-divmod's unsigned checks but
    at 64-bit width.

WHY THIS CONSTRUCT
------------------
Everything tested so far (test-switch, test-divmod, test-funcptr,
test-arrayidx) operates on 32-bit int/unsigned int or pointers - the
riscv64 backend's actual 64-bit arithmetic path (long long / vlong,
using RISC-V's plain 64-bit ADD/SUB/MUL rather than the ADDW/SUBW/MULW
word forms - see gopcode()'s `tword` flag in txt.c, already read while
building test-divmod) has had no coverage at all. This backend has a
32-bit-only heritage (every other Plan9 CPU port is 32-bit), so 64-bit
arithmetic is exactly the kind of feature that could have been bolted
on incompletely even though the simpler width-selection logic already
checked out.

Large 64-bit literals are avoided entirely in this test's source -
sys/src/cmd/cc's literal lexer wasn't available to inspect in this
session (the shared cc/ frontend directory wasn't present in the
mounted overlay at the time), so building every test value from small,
definitely-safe seeds via runtime shifts/multiplies sidesteps any
question about large-literal parsing and keeps this test isolated to
arithmetic codegen specifically.

HOW TO READ THE RESULT
-----------------------
Same convention as the other test-* folders: watch UART0, each line
should read PASS, final line is ALL TESTS PASSED or SOME TESTS FAILED.
LED solid on = done, all passed; fast blink = done, at least one FAIL.

BUILD
-----
mk (produces main.out and main.bin; main.bin is the flashable headerless
output, built with -s to strip Plan9 symbols).
